# Athlos — AI Agent Guide

## Documentation

Read the project docs before coding to understand context and decisions:

- `docs/context.md` — project vision, modules, and future ideas
- `docs/architecture.md` — stack, app structure, entities, and evolution plan
- `docs/requirements.md` — user stories and acceptance criteria by release phase (MoSCoW)
- `docs/development_flow.md` — step-by-step feature implementation guide
- `docs/release.md` — versioning, signing, migrations, build, and publish instructions
- `docs/modules/training.md` — training module features
- `docs/modules/training-periodization.md` — planned periodization evolution
- `docs/modules/diet.md` — diet module features

## Language

- **All code in English** — classes, variables, functions, comments, commits, doc comments
- Portuguese **only** in ARB files (`l10n/`) for user-facing strings

## Naming Conventions

- Classes, enums: `PascalCase`
- Variables, functions, parameters: `camelCase`
- Files and folders: `snake_case`
- Private members: prefix with `_`
- Boolean variables/getters: prefix with `is`, `has`, `can`, `should`
- Global reusable widgets: prefix with `Athlos` (e.g. `AthlosPrimaryButton`, `AthlosStatCard`)

## Dart Best Practices

- Prefer `final` for local variables and fields that don't change
- Use `const` constructors wherever possible
- Prefer expression bodies for simple one-line functions
- Always specify types for public APIs; `var`/`final` is fine for locals with obvious types
- Use `sealed class` or `enum` for finite state types
- Handle all cases with `switch` expressions (exhaustive matching)

## Architecture Rules

See `docs/architecture.md` for full structure. Key rules:

- **Presentation never accesses DataSource directly** — always through a Use Case or repository provider
- **Domain imports nothing from Data or Presentation** — it is the innermost layer
- **Repositories are abstracted by interfaces** in Domain — implementation in Data can be swapped without affecting other layers
- Each feature follows: `domain/` → `data/` → `presentation/`
- **Modules never import each other's domain or data** — shared contracts live in `core/domain/`

## Error Handling

- Use `Result<T>` sealed type (`Success<T>` / `Failure<T>`) for all repository and use case return types
- Use `AppException` sealed hierarchy for typed errors (`DatabaseException`, `ValidationException`, `NotFoundException`, `ConflictException`)
- **Repositories never throw** — catch data-layer exceptions and wrap into `Result.failure(AppException)`
- **Use Cases never throw** — return `Result<T>`
- **Providers use `getOrThrow()`** — in `build()`, Riverpod auto-converts exceptions to `AsyncError`; in mutations, exceptions propagate to the UI caller
- **UI wraps mutation calls in `try/catch`** with error snackbar feedback
- UI consumes `AsyncValue.when(data:, error:, loading:)` for read state

## Use Cases

- Location: `features/<module>/domain/usecases/`
- Single `call()` method per class (callable class pattern)
- Pure Dart — no framework imports (no Flutter, no Riverpod, no Drift)
- Receive repositories via constructor, injected through Riverpod providers
- Use dedicated params class when more than 2 parameters
- **Skip for simple CRUD** with no business logic — controller calls repository directly
- **Required when**: validation, business rules, multiple repositories, or expected complexity growth

## Riverpod

- Use `@riverpod` annotation (code generation) for all providers
- Use `ref.watch` in `build()` methods; `ref.read` for one-off actions (e.g. button callbacks)
- Use `ref.listen` for reacting to external state changes (not for mutation error handling — use `try/catch` at the call site instead)
- Use `AsyncValue` pattern (`.when(data:, error:, loading:)`) for async state in the UI
- Keep providers small and focused — one responsibility per provider
- Repository providers go in `data/repositories/`; Use Case providers in `domain/usecases/`; UI state providers in `presentation/providers/`

## Drift (database)

- Versioned migrations — never alter old migrations, always create new ones
- Table names in plural (exercises, workouts, equipments)
- Use DAOs to organize queries by entity/feature
- Use type converters for enums and complex types
- Keep table definitions in dedicated files under `data/datasources/`
- Use `transaction()` for atomic multi-table writes

## go_router

- Route paths as constants in a dedicated file (e.g. `core/router/route_paths.dart`)
- Use `ShellRoute` for bottom navigation (upgrade to `StatefulShellRoute` when tabs need to preserve local widget state)
- Use redirect guards for future auth flows
- Use `GoRouterState` extension for typed route parameters

## Design Tokens

- Never hardcode spacing, radius, elevation, or animation durations
- Use token classes: `AthlosSpacing`, `AthlosRadius`, `AthlosElevation`, `AthlosDurations`
- Colors via `Theme.of(context).colorScheme` — typography via `Theme.of(context).textTheme`
- Token files live in `core/theme/`

## UI / Flutter

- Never hardcode colors — always use `Theme.of(context).colorScheme`
- Never hardcode strings — use ARB files via `AppLocalizations`
- Never hardcode spacing/radius — use Design Tokens (`AthlosSpacing.md`, `AthlosRadius.sm`)
- Always add a `Key` to widgets in lists (`ValueKey`, `ObjectKey`)
- Prefer `const` widgets to reduce rebuilds
- Use `SizedBox` instead of `Container` when only size is needed
- Prefer `gap` package or `SizedBox` over `Padding` for spacing between widgets

## Loading States

- **Primary content**: use `Skeletonizer(enabled: asyncValue.isLoading)` wrapping the real widget with placeholder data
  - Placeholder data lives in the **presentation layer** (local constant in the screen file)
  - Domain entities must NOT have `.fake()` factories or test-only constructors
  - Pattern: `if (hasError) → error widget; else → Skeletonizer(enabled: isLoading, child: content(data ?? placeholders))`
- **Inline sections** (chips, badges, small indicators): keep `CircularProgressIndicator(strokeWidth: 2)`
- **Action-in-progress** (save buttons, FAB): keep `CircularProgressIndicator` inside the button
- **App startup**: `SplashScreen` at `/splash` route handles the loading → redirect flow via GoRouter

## Widget Organization

- Global reusable widgets go in `core/widgets/<type>/` organized by type:
  - `buttons/`, `cards/`, `inputs/`, `feedback/`, `layout/`, `overlays/`
- Feature-specific widgets go in `features/<module>/presentation/widgets/`
- **If a widget imports from `features/*/domain/`, it belongs to the feature, NOT to `core/`**
- Extract to `core/widgets/` only when a widget appears in **two or more features**
